{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0d98e92a-bedf-444f-8a45-1492a318d0a6","content":"## What happened\n\n.NET has been progressively deprecating DSA (FIPS 186-2) as a legacy algorithm. On macOS, Apple's native cryptography frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) have **never** supported DSA — earlier .NET versions worked around this by loading OpenSSL at runtime. In .NET 11, that OpenSSL-based DSA fallback on macOS was removed, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**.\n\nLinux and Windows still work because Linux uses OpenSSL system-wide and Windows has CNG, both of which still expose DSA.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have two options, depending on your constraints:\n\n### Option 1 — Migrate away from DSA (preferred)\n\nIf you control the signing side, move to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (`ECDsa.Create()` / the new `EdDSA` APIs). DSA key sizes ≤ 1024 bits are considered insecure, and NIST formally deprecated DSA in 2023.\n\n### Option 2 — Use a managed DSA implementation (for legacy verification)\n\nIf you must keep verifying existing DSA signatures, use **BouncyCastle**, which is a fully-managed implementation with no native OS dependency:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\n// Import the existing DSA public key\nvar publicKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n\n// Verify a signature\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signatureBytes);\n```\n\nThis runs on all platforms with no native crypto dependency. Use this as a bridge while you plan a migration to modern algorithms.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a8e8b561-ee66-4754-9736-fec7bedf2ec7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason through this based on my knowledge of .NET's cryptography evolution.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Let me explain what happened:\n\nStarting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been progressively removing older, less secure cryptographic algorithms. DSA (the original DSA, not ECDSA) has been considered obsolete for a long time. \n\nOn macOS specifically, Apple's Security framework and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit don't natively support DSA. In earlier .NET versions, the DSA implementation on macOS was provided through OpenSSL (via the `System.Security.Cryptography` package which bundled or referenced OpenSSL). \n\n\nIn .NET 8, DSA was marked as obsolete with warnings, and Microsoft started restricting its availability on certain platforms. By .NET 9, the breaking change hit macOS—DSA support was removed when using Apple's native cryptographic backend instead of OpenSSL.\n\nGiven the timeline (current date May 2026), .NET 11 would be in preview now, following the release schedule of .NET 10 in November 2025. The core issue is that .NET has been gradually phasing out DSA, and on macOS specifically, the shift away from OpenSSL to native crypto APIs removed DSA support entirely. throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS as part of the broader deprecation effort. For workarounds, they could use BouncyCastle for a managed DSA implementation, migrate to ECDSA or EdDSA if they control both signing and verification, or implement OpenSSL via P/Invoke if they only need to verify existing signatures. I should give them a straightforward answer about this platform change without needing to search for specifics.","outputTokens":1515,"requestId":"884B:20DE42:45F36D:50FAC0:69FA9CD0"},"id":"095b0cad-1dd4-456f-af15-43d7d037363d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:44:18.832Z","parentId":"86334398-50e4-475e-923f-1e7c148d6923"}
